00:29:11.030 --> 00:29:17.040
Hilke, thanks so much for this inspiring talk and for

00:29:17.040 --> 00:29:24.910
being the first in the atmosphere who speaks publicly about bringing artists

00:29:24.940 --> 00:29:26.890
to the protocol.

00:29:26.910 --> 00:29:32.780
I am really impressed by the two to the end.

00:29:32.790 --> 00:29:36.620
But I want to comment on the, actually, you already

00:29:36.620 --> 00:29:40.090
answered the question in a way, but when you talked about

00:29:40.120 --> 00:29:44.300
doing the artist of the month, I was thinking of this

00:29:44.300 --> 00:29:49.170
could actually create some kind of competition with attention economy.

00:29:49.190 --> 00:29:52.360
So, because any, like, any kind of institution is

00:29:52.360 --> 00:29:55.960
bringing the artist of the month and this is creating some kind

00:29:55.960 --> 00:29:58.890
of where should I look for the artist of the month.

00:29:58.910 --> 00:30:02.760
And I was thinking what we could do instead in the atmosphere

00:30:02.770 --> 00:30:06.810
is like building tools for music circles, like small groups of

00:30:06.850 --> 00:30:07.500
people.

00:30:07.510 --> 00:30:10.280
I mean, you answered this already now, but this is

00:30:10.290 --> 00:30:12.610
something maybe we should not forget.

00:30:12.630 --> 00:30:15.480
So, like, people bring together in a room and then

00:30:15.480 --> 00:30:18.270
don't have the artist in, like artist of the month

00:30:18.270 --> 00:30:21.180
, but have a group of people who are artists, but

00:30:21.180 --> 00:30:24.180
are at the same time people who enjoy art.

00:30:24.190 --> 00:30:30.140
And then maybe they can select among themselves the artist who should

00:30:30.140 --> 00:30:35.140
be in the spotlight for this event or for another event.

00:30:35.150 --> 00:30:38.780
So, yeah, and I really appreciate that you think of

00:30:38.780 --> 00:30:42.380
, was it the, including the creation process.

00:30:42.390 --> 00:30:44.990
So, this is not a question, I should have said

00:30:44.990 --> 00:30:47.980
this before, it's just, I'm just impressed and

00:30:47.980 --> 00:30:51.660
I want to say thank you for doing this for us.

00:30:51.670 --> 00:30:53.460
Yeah, thank you.

00:30:53.470 --> 00:30:56.590
Yeah, definitely the artist of the month, I was also

00:30:56.590 --> 00:30:59.690
not really sure because it's some kind of curation,

00:30:59.730 --> 00:31:01.700
but it couldn't be.

00:31:01.710 --> 00:31:03.580
I think I was thinking, it shouldn't be, I

00:31:03.580 --> 00:31:06.140
was thinking a bit in the same direction, maybe it should

00:31:06.140 --> 00:31:09.340
be like, do we say estafete in English?

00:31:09.350 --> 00:31:11.670
I don't know, like you give, there is one

00:31:11.670 --> 00:31:14.800
artist and they give it to the next or something like that

00:31:14.850 --> 00:31:15.070
.

00:31:15.190 --> 00:31:16.840
Oh, like a torch, pass the torch.

00:31:16.870 --> 00:31:18.730
Torch, pass the torch, yeah, something like that

00:31:18.730 --> 00:31:18.930
.

00:31:18.950 --> 00:31:21.760
Yeah, it's, I mean, it's not about

00:31:21.760 --> 00:31:25.680
nominating an artist, for me it's more about going

00:31:25.680 --> 00:31:28.780
really deeply into someone's work.

00:31:29.790 --> 00:31:33.920
Yeah, it's not about choosing something, it's about

00:31:33.920 --> 00:31:37.420
finding depth in, in a story of one artist.

00:31:37.430 --> 00:31:39.020
But thank you for your comment.

00:31:39.140 --> 00:31:47.420
What do you hope to do next with 2N,

00:31:47.420 --> 00:31:49.620
what do you want to do next, yeah.

00:31:49.700 --> 00:31:54.560
Um, yeah, I think, what was nice about this

00:31:54.560 --> 00:31:57.080
, it took me only two days to program it and I

00:31:57.080 --> 00:31:58.860
had more time for music.

00:31:58.870 --> 00:32:01.130
I think this is one of the exciting things now with,

00:32:01.130 --> 00:32:03.220
with, with, with, with, uh, agents.

00:32:03.230 --> 00:32:06.490
Um, I'm certainly going to make more music.

00:32:06.620 --> 00:32:10.350
So, the concept is that you need to be with more

00:32:10.350 --> 00:32:12.200
and more people, right.

00:32:12.270 --> 00:32:15.390
Um, it's, I think it's also challenging from

00:32:15.390 --> 00:32:18.490
a musical perspective, how do you make that work together.

00:32:18.510 --> 00:32:20.830
Um, I think it's, like, now there are

00:32:20.840 --> 00:32:24.140
two versions, but, like, if there are four people

00:32:24.140 --> 00:32:26.660
, maybe it would be cool that there are, like,

00:32:26.660 --> 00:32:30.130
four parts that also work on their own, but then together

00:32:30.130 --> 00:32:32.500
, and then they would be different.

00:32:32.510 --> 00:32:34.660
And if you would be only two people, then it would

00:32:34.660 --> 00:32:35.340
also work.

00:32:35.350 --> 00:32:37.720
Like, that's the, that kind of thing that I

00:32:37.730 --> 00:32:40.700
find interesting as, as a composer or some writer.

00:32:40.710 --> 00:32:42.710
Um, yeah, I, I can imagine, I don

00:32:42.710 --> 00:32:44.620
't know if it's worth it, it's, it

00:32:44.620 --> 00:32:46.700
's, it's, it's sort of a game,

00:32:46.700 --> 00:32:50.980
but maybe it's a model that more artists want to use

00:32:50.980 --> 00:32:57.050
and then we can make it into some crazy music service.

00:32:57.180 --> 00:32:59.060
Cool.

00:32:59.070 --> 00:33:01.060
Thank you so much, Hilke.

00:33:01.070 --> 00:33:02.060
Thank you.

00:33:02.070 --> 00:33:03.280
